{"id":2339,"date":"2020-10-15T21:00:00","date_gmt":"2020-10-15T10:00:00","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/?p=2339"},"modified":"2020-10-15T14:44:45","modified_gmt":"2020-10-15T03:44:45","slug":"particle-wo","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/particle-wo\/","title":{"rendered":"The Japanese particle &#8220;wo&#8221; (o): What it is and how to use it"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>The particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> is one of the most common and useful particles. It is also one of the simplest to understand.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>This is great for two reasons:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><li>With just a few examples, we can easily see how to use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> in a sentence, as you will see below.<\/li><li>We can take advantage of the simplicity of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> to try to better understand some more general concepts related to <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/japanese-sentence-structure\/\">Japanese sentence structure<\/a> &#8211; concepts that can be applied to other particles too.<\/li><\/ol>\n\n\n\n<p>In this article we will look at what <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> is, how to use it in a sentence, and a few things to be careful of. We&#8217;ll also touch on some more advanced concepts that give some insight into the bigger picture of the Japanese grammar system.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<!--more-->\n\n\n\n<div class=\"rw-toc\">\n<div class=\"rw-toc-title\">Table of Contents<\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#what-is-wo\"><strong>What is <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span>?<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#vs-english\"><strong>Comparing <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> with English<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#complex-objects\"><strong>More complex objects<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#gotchas\"><strong>Things to be careful of with the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span><\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<div class=\"rw-sub-contents\"><div><a href=\"#objectless-verbs\">Some verbs can&#8217;t be used with <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span><\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#not-mandatory\">The object doesn&#8217;t always have to be stated<\/a><\/div>\n<div class=\"rw-sub-contents\"><div><a href=\"#objects-english\">The need for objects in English<\/a><\/div><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#not-like-english\">Some verbs don&#8217;t work like their English counterparts<\/a><\/div><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#key-takeaways\"><strong>Key Takeaways<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><\/div>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"what-is-wo\"><strong>What is <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span>?<\/strong><\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The purpose of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> is quite straightforward:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><strong data-rich-text-format-boundary=\"true\">The particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span>, usually pronounced \u201co\u201d, marks the object of the verb \u2013 that is, the person or thing that the action is done to.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>It appears in our <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/japanese-sentence-structure\/\">sentence structure diagram<\/a> in the &#8220;Other information&#8221; section, as shown:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large ilRom\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"517\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/00-wo-sentence-structure-romaji-1024x517.png\" alt=\"Object in Japanese sentences structure (romaji)\" class=\"wp-image-2498\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/00-wo-sentence-structure-romaji-1024x517.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/00-wo-sentence-structure-romaji-300x151.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/00-wo-sentence-structure-romaji-768x388.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/00-wo-sentence-structure-romaji.png 1488w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large ilKana\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"517\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/00-wo-sentence-structure-romaji-1024x517.png\" alt=\"Object in Japanese sentences structure (romaji)\" class=\"wp-image-2498\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/00-wo-sentence-structure-romaji-1024x517.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/00-wo-sentence-structure-romaji-300x151.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/00-wo-sentence-structure-romaji-768x388.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/10\/00-wo-sentence-structure-romaji.png 1488w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>(If you haven&#8217;t seen this before, <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/japanese-sentence-structure\/\">read here<\/a>.)<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Let\u2019s look at an example:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"189\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/01-sushi-ate-1024x189.png\" alt=\"Tar\u014d wa sushi wo tabemashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2430\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/01-sushi-ate-1024x189.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/01-sushi-ate-300x55.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/01-sushi-ate-768x142.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/01-sushi-ate-1536x283.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/01-sushi-ate-2048x378.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Taro ate sushi.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">Taro ate sushi.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">tar\u014d wa sushi wo tabemashita.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u305f\u308d\u3046 \u306f \u3059\u3057 \u3092 \u305f\u3079\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u592a\u90ce<rt>\u305f\u308d\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f\u3059\u3057\u3092<ruby>\u98df<rt>\u305f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3079\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Here, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> comes after <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;sushi&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3059\u3057\u300d<\/span>, and this tells us that sushi is the thing that was eaten.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The same applies regardless of what action is being described. Whatever comes before <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> is the thing the action was done to.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Let\u2019s try a couple more examples:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/02-book-read-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Tar\u014d wa hon wo yomimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2431\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/02-book-read-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/02-book-read-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/02-book-read-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/02-book-read-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/02-book-read-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Taro read a book.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">Taro read a book.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">tar\u014d wa hon wo yomimashita.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u305f\u308d\u3046 \u306f \u307b\u3093 \u3092 \u3088\u307f\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u592a\u90ce<rt>\u305f\u308d\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<ruby>\u672c<rt>\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u8aad<rt>\u3088<\/rt><\/ruby>\u307f\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>The book is the thing that was read, and we know this because <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;hon&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u672c<rt>\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> is followed by <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/03-bought-bicycle-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Tar\u014d wa jitensha wo kaimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2432\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/03-bought-bicycle-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/03-bought-bicycle-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/03-bought-bicycle-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/03-bought-bicycle-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/03-bought-bicycle-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Taro bought a bicycle.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">Taro bought a bicycle.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">tar\u014d wa jitensha wo kaimashita.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u305f\u308d\u3046 \u306f \u3058\u3066\u3093\u3057\u3083 \u3092 \u304b\u3044\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u592a\u90ce<rt>\u305f\u308d\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<ruby>\u81ea\u8ee2\u8eca<rt>\u3058\u3066\u3093\u3057\u3083<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u8cb7<rt>\u304b<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3044\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Again, because <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> comes after <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;jitensha&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u81ea\u8ee2\u8eca<rt>\u3058\u3066\u3093\u3057\u3083<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span>, we know that it was a bike that Taro bought.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"vs-english\"><strong>Comparing &#8220;wo&#8221; with English<\/strong><\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>You may not really think about it often, or at all, but the concept of the \u201cobject\u201d in terms of Japanese grammar is the same as in English. The only real difference is how it is used in a sentence.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In English, the object always comes after the verb, usually directly after. That was the case in each of our examples. Here\u2019s the first one again:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p class=\"english\">Taro ate sushi.<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>\u201cSushi\u201d comes after the verb, \u201cate\u201d, so it is the sushi that the act of eating was done to.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In English, it is the <strong>word order<\/strong> that tells us this.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>If we re-arranged those three words, the meaning would change, or not make sense at all\u2026<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p class=\"english\">Sushi ate Taro. (???)<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>In Japanese, regardless of <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/japanese-word-order\/\">what order the words appear in<\/a>, <strong>the thing directly before <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> is the object of the verb<\/strong> \u2013 that is, the thing the action was done to.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"complex-objects\"><strong>More complex objects<\/strong><\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The examples so far have been very simple sentences with very simple objects. Let\u2019s look at an example with a slightly more complicated one.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">Taro watched an interesting movie.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">tar\u014d wa omoshiroi eiga wo mimashita.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u305f\u308d\u3046 \u306f \u304a\u3082\u3057\u308d\u3044 \u3048\u3044\u304c \u3092 \u307f\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u592a\u90ce<rt>\u305f\u308d\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<ruby>\u9762\u767d<rt>\u304a\u3082\u3057\u308d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3044<ruby>\u6620\u753b<rt>\u3048\u3044\u304c<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u898b<rt>\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Here, instead of being a single word, the object is a phrase consisting of two words \u2013 <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;omoshiroi&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u9762\u767d<rt>\u304a\u3082\u3057\u308d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3044\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;eiga&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u6620\u753b<rt>\u3048\u3044\u304c<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span>. This brings us to an important point:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><strong data-rich-text-format-boundary=\"true\">The \u201cobject\u201d of a sentence is one \u201cthing\u201d, not necessarily a single word.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u201cThing\u201d in this context could be anything, or even multiple things that are grouped together.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In this example, that \u201cthing\u201d is <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;omoshiroi eiga&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u9762\u767d<rt>\u304a\u3082\u3057\u308d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3044<ruby>\u6620\u753b<rt>\u3048\u3044\u304c<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span>, or in English, \u201can interesting movie\u201d. <strong>This is what the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> applies to.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Here it is in our diagram:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/04-interesting-movie-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Tar\u014d wa omoshiroi eiga wo mimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2433\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/04-interesting-movie-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/04-interesting-movie-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/04-interesting-movie-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/04-interesting-movie-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/04-interesting-movie-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Taro watched an interesting movie.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>As a whole, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;omoshiroi eiga&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u9762\u767d<rt>\u304a\u3082\u3057\u308d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3044<ruby>\u6620\u753b<rt>\u3048\u3044\u304c<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> is what we call a <strong>noun phrase<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>A noun is a single word that refers to something, like \u201cbook\u201d or \u201cmovie\u201d. A noun phrase is simply any phrase that, <em>as a whole<\/em>, refers to a single \u201cthing\u201d as described above.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>(By the way, a single noun like <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;eiga&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u6620\u753b<rt>\u3048\u3044\u304c<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> is, by itself, a noun phrase \u2013 just a very simple one).<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span>, therefore, can take any noun phrase, no matter how complicated, and turn it into the object of a verb.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Let\u2019s now look at an example of a more complex noun phrase. This is more advanced in a few ways, so don\u2019t worry too much if it doesn&#8217;t make sense to you. This is mostly to highlight the fact that the object can be far more complex than a single word.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/05-recommended-movie-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Tar\u014d wa tomodachi ni susumerareta omoshiroi eiga wo mimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2434\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/05-recommended-movie-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/05-recommended-movie-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/05-recommended-movie-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/05-recommended-movie-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/05-recommended-movie-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Taro watched an interesting movie that was recommended by a friend.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">Taro watched <u>an interesting movie that was recommended by a friend<\/u>.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">tar\u014d wa <u>tomodachi ni susumerareta omoshiroi eiga<\/u> wo mimashita.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u305f\u308d\u3046 \u306f <u>\u3068\u3082\u3060\u3061 \u306b \u3059\u3059\u3081\u3089\u308c\u305f \u304a\u3082\u3057\u308d\u3044 \u3048\u3044\u304c<\/u> \u3092 \u307f\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u592a\u90ce<rt>\u305f\u308d\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<u><ruby>\u53cb\u9054<rt>\u3068\u3082\u3060\u3061<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u52e7<rt>\u3059\u3059<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3081\u3089\u308c\u305f<ruby>\u9762\u767d<rt>\u304a\u3082\u3057\u308d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3044<ruby>\u6620\u753b<rt>\u3048\u3044\u304c<\/rt><\/ruby><\/u>\u3092<ruby>\u898b<rt>\u307f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Here, the object is <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;tomodachi ni susumerareta omoshiroi eiga&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u53cb\u9054<rt>\u3068\u3082\u3060\u3061<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u52e7<rt>\u3059\u3059<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3081\u3089\u308c\u305f<ruby>\u9762\u767d<rt>\u304a\u3082\u3057\u308d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3044<ruby>\u6620\u753b<rt>\u3048\u3044\u304c<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span>, or \u201can interesting movie that was recommended by a friend\u201d.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>That whole noun phrase is what <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> applies to.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>There are a number of ways that noun phrases can be formed, but the last word in any noun phrase will always be a noun.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>If you want to learn more about simple and complex noun phrases and all of the different ways of forming them, <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/\">Chapter 10 of my book covers them in detail<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"gotchas\"><strong>Things to be careful of with the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span><\/strong><\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Although <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> is fairly straightforward by itself, there are a few things that it may help to be aware of.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"objectless-verbs\">Some verbs can&#8217;t be used with <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span><\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>First of all, it\u2019s important to recognize that <strong>not all verbs can take an object<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Some actions invariably involve someone doing something to something else. For example, when you read, there must be something that you are reading. The same is true when eating, watching, buying, etc.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>However, some actions can never have an object, meaning there isn\u2019t something that the action is done to. Here\u2019s an example:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"192\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/06-taro-slept-1024x192.png\" alt=\"Tar\u014d wa nemashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2435\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/06-taro-slept-1024x192.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/06-taro-slept-300x56.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/06-taro-slept-768x144.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/06-taro-slept-1536x288.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/06-taro-slept-2048x384.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Taro slept.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n\t<p class=\"english\">Taro slept.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"romaji\">Tar\u014d wa nemashita.<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kana\">\u305f\u308d\u3046 \u306f \u306d\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n\t<p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u592a\u90ce<rt>\u305f\u308d\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<ruby>\u5bdd<rt>\u306d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>When we read, we read something, but we don\u2019t ever sleep <em>something<\/em>. We might sleep <em>somewhere<\/em>, or <em>on something<\/em>, but we don\u2019t, for example, \u201csleep a bed\u201d.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Some verbs simply do not take objects, and should therefore never be associated directly with the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"not-mandatory\">The object doesn&#8217;t always have to be stated<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>On a related note, <strong>just because a verb can take an object does not mean that it must<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Let\u2019s use the \u201ceat\u201d example again. When we eat, we always eat something, but we don\u2019t necessarily need to specify what that is. In both English and Japanese, we can simply say:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"192\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/07-taro-ate-1024x192.png\" alt=\"Tar\u014d wa tabemashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2436\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/07-taro-ate-1024x192.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/07-taro-ate-300x56.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/07-taro-ate-768x144.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/07-taro-ate-1536x288.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/07-taro-ate-2048x384.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Taro ate.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">Taro ate.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">tar\u014d wa tabemashita.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u305f\u308d\u3046 \u306f \u305f\u3079\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u592a\u90ce<rt>\u305f\u308d\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<ruby>\u98df<rt>\u305f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3079\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>We can add an object if we want to, but we don\u2019t have to. Something can be involved in an action without explicitly being spoken of.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>This exclusion of objects is actually even more common in Japanese than it is in English. Japanese relies heavily on context, meaning that if it is known, for example, that we are talking about \u201csushi\u201d, we can effectively say, \u201cTaro ate sushi,\u201d without even mentioning an object.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>English handles this a little differently. Here\u2019s a short dialogue that illustrates this.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<style>\n.dialog{\n  display: inline-block;\n  padding: 10px 15px;\n  border-radius: 10px;\n  text-align: left;\n}\n<\/style>\n\n<div><strong>Miho:<\/strong><\/div>\n<div style=\"border: 1px solid #00ee00;\" class=\"example dialog\"><p class=\"english\">The sushi is gone!<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">sushi ga naku narimashita!<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u3059\u3057 \u304c \u306a\u304f \u306a\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\uff01<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u3059\u3057\u304c\u306a\u304f\u306a\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\uff01<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<div style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<div><strong>Kenta:<\/strong><\/div>\n<div style=\"border: 1px solid #0000ee;\" class=\"example dialog\"><p class=\"english\">Taro ate it.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">tar\u014d ga tabemashita<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u305f\u308d\u3046 \u304c \u305f\u3079\u307e\u3057\u305f<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u592a\u90ce<rt>\u305f\u308d\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304c<ruby>\u98df<rt>\u305f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3079\u307e\u3057\u305f<\/p><\/div>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Notice the difference between the English and Japanese versions of Kenta\u2019s response?<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In English, Kenta says \u201cit\u201d, referring to the sushi, but in Japanese, he doesn\u2019t refer to the sushi at all.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In both cases, it is understood what has been eaten, but English requires us to include an object (in this case \u201cit\u201d) when there is one specified*.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We use \u201cit\u201d in order to meet this requirement without also being absurdly repetitive. Without \u201cit\u201d and other pronouns, we would constantly be referring to things by name.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Japanese, however, doesn\u2019t have such a requirement. If the object (or any other information, for that matter) is understood from context, we can just omit it, like Kenta has done.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-group rw-sidebar\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container is-layout-flow wp-block-group-is-layout-flow\">\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"objects-english\"><strong>*The need for objects in English<\/strong><\/h4>\n\n\n\n<p>Allow me to clarify something.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In the space of a few paragraphs I have said that English requires us to include an object when there is one specified, while also giving an example that appears to break that rule: \u201cTaro ate.\u201d This seems contradictory, but it\u2019s not.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>There is a subtle but important difference between the following two sentences:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p class=\"english\">Taro ate.<\/p>\n<p class=\"english\">Taro ate it.<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>The first describes a general action that Taro performed \u2013 that he ate. The second refers to a specific thing and explains that Taro ate it. These are not the same. If we modify our earlier example, we can see why:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div><strong>Miho:<\/strong><\/div>\n<div style=\"border: 1px solid #00ee00;\" class=\"example dialog\"><p class=\"english\">The sushi is gone!<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">sushi ga naku narimashita!<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u3059\u3057 \u304c \u306a\u304f \u306a\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\uff01<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u3059\u3057\u304c\u306a\u304f\u306a\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\uff01<\/p>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<div style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<div><strong>Kenta:<\/strong><\/div>\n<div style=\"border: 1px solid #0000ee;\" class=\"example dialog\"><p class=\"english\">Taro ate.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">tar\u014d ga tabemashita<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u305f\u308d\u3046 \u304c \u305f\u3079\u307e\u3057\u305f<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u592a\u90ce<rt>\u305f\u308d\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304c<ruby>\u98df<rt>\u305f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3079\u307e\u3057\u305f<\/p><\/div>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>The English here just sounds wrong. By not saying \u201cit\u201d, it sounds like Kenta is just changing the topic and making a general statement that Taro has had food. However, if Kenta wants to refer to the sushi as the thing Taro ate, he must include &#8220;it&#8221;.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>So, like I said &#8211; if talking about a specific object, that object must be included in English.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>How does this affect Japanese? Well, it doesn\u2019t, but it may affect how you interpret Japanese.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>As an English speaker, you are used to objects being included every time they are present \u2013 either directly, or via pronouns like &#8220;it&#8221;. But both versions of the above dialogue are exactly the same in Japanese, even though their English translations are different.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>So, just keep in mind that many verbs can be used with or without an object, but even when no object is specified (using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span>), it is possible that the sentence is actually talking about a specific object. Of course, it could also just be a more general statement (like \u201cTaro ate.\u201d).<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In most situations, it should be fairly obvious from context.<\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"not-like-english\">Some verbs don&#8217;t work like their English counterparts<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Lastly, there are a few situations where something that might be considered an object in English is not an object in Japanese. This is mostly limited to a few particular verbs. Here\u2019s an example:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"198\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/08-train-rode-1024x198.png\" alt=\"Tar\u014d wa densha ni norimashita.\" class=\"wp-image-2437\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/08-train-rode-1024x198.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/08-train-rode-300x58.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/08-train-rode-768x149.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/08-train-rode-1536x297.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/08-train-rode-2048x397.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>Taro rode the train.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">Taro rode the train.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">tar\u014d wa densha ni norimashita.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u305f\u308d\u3046 \u306f \u3067\u3093\u3057\u3083 \u306b \u306e\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u592a\u90ce<rt>\u305f\u308d\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<ruby>\u96fb\u8eca<rt>\u3067\u3093\u3057\u3083<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u4e57<rt>\u306e<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>The verb <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;norimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u4e57<rt>\u306e<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>, meaning \u201cto ride\u201d, treats the thing that is being ridden not as an object, but as a destination. <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;Norimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u4e57<rt>\u306e<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> can&#8217;t really take an object, so <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> should never be used in direct connection with it.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>This seems a bit unintuitive coming from English, since we would say that Taro \u201crode the train\u201d using the same syntax as when we say \u201cTaro ate the sushi\u201d. It is just one of those little peculiar differences between how each language phrases certain descriptions.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Another example of this is the word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;omoimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u601d<rt>\u304a\u3082<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3044\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>, meaning \u201cto think\u201d.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In an English sentence like, \u201cI think Taro ate the sushi\u201d, it might look like the phrase, \u201cTaro ate the sushi\u201d is the object of the verb \u201cthink\u201d. It&#8217;s not, but it kinda looks like it might be, since it comes after &#8220;think&#8221; and is the thing that is being thought.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Importantly, however, in Japanese the equivalent phrase would not be marked by <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> because it is not treated as an object. Instead, we would use the quoting particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;to&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3068\u300d<\/span>. Let&#8217;s see:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">I think Taro ate the sushi.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">watashi wa tar\u014d ga sushi wo tabeta to omoimasu<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306f \u305f\u308d\u3046 \u304c \u3059\u3057 \u3092 \u305f\u3079\u305f \u3068 \u304a\u3082\u3044\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<ruby>\u592a\u90ce<rt>\u305f\u308d\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304c\u3059\u3057\u3092<ruby>\u98df<rt>\u305f<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3079\u305f\u3068<ruby>\u601d<rt>\u304a\u3082<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3044\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>This fits into our diagram like this:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"215\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/09-i-think-taro-ate-the-sushi-1024x215.png\" alt=\"watashi wa tar\u014d ga sushi wo tabeta to omoimasu.\" class=\"wp-image-2443\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/09-i-think-taro-ate-the-sushi-1024x215.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/09-i-think-taro-ate-the-sushi-300x63.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/09-i-think-taro-ate-the-sushi-768x161.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/09-i-think-taro-ate-the-sushi-1536x322.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2020\/09\/09-i-think-taro-ate-the-sushi-2048x429.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption>I think Taro ate the sushi.<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>And yes, that&#8217;s a mini sentence diagram inside the quotation element of a bigger sentence diagram. Welcome to The Matrix.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"key-takeaways\"><strong>Key Takeaways<\/strong><\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The role of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> is fairly straight-forward:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><strong>The particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span> marks the object of the verb \u2013 that is, the thing the action was done to.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>To use it correctly, we just need to understand a few simple concepts, and be careful of a few exceptional situations:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><li>Unlike English, word order does not affect whether or not something is the object of a verb \u2013 the object is always the thing marked by the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3092\u300d<\/span><\/li><li>An object is a single \u201cthing\u201d in the form of a noun phrase, which could be simple or complex \u2013 it is not necessarily a single word.<\/li><li>Not every sentence has to have an object.<\/li><li>Some verbs (such as <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;neru&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u5bdd<rt>\u306d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308b\u300d<\/span>, meaning \u201csleep\u201d) never take an object (because it doesn\u2019t make sense).<\/li><li>For a few English verbs that normally have an object (eg. \u201cride\u201d), the Japanese equivalent (eg. <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;norimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u4e57<rt>\u306e<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308a\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>) treats the English object as something else (eg. a destination).<\/li><\/ul>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>The particle &#8220;wo&#8221;\u300c\u3092\u300d is one of the most common and useful particles. It is also one of the simplest to understand. This is great for two reasons: With just a few examples, we can easily see how to use &#8220;wo&#8221;\u300c\u3092\u300d in a sentence, as you will see below. We can take advantage of the simplicity [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":4,"featured_media":2497,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"footnotes":""},"categories":[4,5],"tags":[],"class_list":["post-2339","post","type-post","status-publish","format-standard","has-post-thumbnail","hentry","category-grammar","category-structure","post-wrapper","thrv_wrapper"],"yoast_head":"<!-- This site is optimized with the Yoast SEO plugin v25.9 - https:\/\/yoast.com\/wordpress\/plugins\/seo\/ -->\n<title>The Japanese particle &quot;wo&quot; (o): What it is and how to use it - 80\/20 Japanese<\/title>\n<meta name=\"robots\" content=\"index, follow, max-snippet: